1. Description¶

This data originally came from Crowdflower's Data for Everyone library. It contains whether the sentiment of the tweets in this set was positive, neutral, or negative for six US airlines As the original source says,

"A sentiment analysis job about the problems of each major U.S. airline. Twitter data was scraped from February of 2015 and contributors were asked to first classify positive, negative, and neutral tweets, followed by categorizing negative reasons (such as "late flight" or "rude service"). The data we're providing on Kaggle is a slightly reformatted version of the original source. It includes both a CSV file and SQLite database. The code that does these transformations is available on GitHub

2.1. Wordcloud of postive and negative tweets¶

In [5]:
ps_df = df_data[df_data['airline_sentiment']=='positive']
pv_words = ' '.join(ps_df['text'])
pv_word = ' '.join([word for word in pv_words.split() if 'http' not in word and not word.startswith('@') and word != 'RT' ])
pv_wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=STOPWORDS, background_color='blue').generate(pv_word)

nn_df=df_data[df_data['airline_sentiment']=='neutral']
nn_words = ' '.join(nn_df['text'])
nn_word = ' '.join([word for word in nn_words.split() if 'http' not in word and not word.startswith('@') and word != 'RT' and word !='wa'])
nn_wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=STOPWORDS, background_color='white').generate(nn_word)

nv_df=df_data[df_data['airline_sentiment']=='negative']
nv_words = ' '.join(nv_df['text'])
nv_word = ' '.join([word for word in nv_words.split() if 'http' not in word and not word.startswith('@') and word != 'RT' and word !='wa'])
nv_wordcloud = WordCloud(stopwords=STOPWORDS, background_color='pink').generate(nv_word)

2.1. Univariate Data Analysis¶

Looking at the table above we can see few features on interest that we can explore individually here ('airline_sentiment', 'negativereason', 'airline', 'retweet_count')

Airline Sentiment¶

  • From the visual, it is fair to say that most passengers do not appreciate their flights.
  • There are tweets of three types (postive, neutral and negative) in the ratio.
